# 63. Institutional herding

> The safest place to be wrong is in a crowd of experts who are wrong the same way you are — which is precisely how a market of the wise becomes a mob.

## The idea

Picture a fund manager who studies a stock closely and concludes it is overpriced. Everyone else is buying it. The manager now faces two ways of being right and two ways of being wrong, and they are not symmetrical. If she sells and she is right, she wins — modestly. If she buys with the herd and the herd is right, she also wins. But consider the losing branches. If she buys with the herd and the herd is wrong, she is one of many; her clients shrug, her peers commiserate, nobody was clever enough to see it coming. If she sells alone and turns out wrong, she is the fool who bet against the market on a hunch — and she is fired. Weigh those four outcomes not by whether the position makes money but by what happens to *her*, and the arithmetic is stark. It pays to buy the stock she believes is overpriced.

This is institutional herding: professionals copying one another not because they are ignorant, not because they have caught some emotional fever, but because the incentive structure they work inside makes conformity the rational career move. Being wrong when everyone else is wrong is survivable. Being wrong alone is fatal. So the sensible thing — for the person, not for the market — is to cluster around the consensus, to hug the benchmark, to hold roughly what the peer next door is holding, even when private judgment says otherwise. The result is a market that looks like a gathering of independent experts and behaves like a single, crowded, correlated bet.

## The origin

The seed is in John Maynard Keynes, writing in 1936 in *The General Theory of Employment, Interest and Money*. In his famous chapter on long-term expectation, Keynes observed that the professional investor is not rewarded for being right in some absolute sense but for being right in a way that is legible and defensible to clients and employers. "Worldly wisdom," he wrote, "teaches that it is better for reputation to fail conventionally than to succeed unconventionally." The line is often quoted for its wit; its real force is diagnostic. Keynes had identified that the incentives facing the money manager reward conformity over correctness, and that a market run by such people would systematically prefer the comfortable consensus to the lonely truth.

The idea waited half a century for its formal engine. In 1990, David Scharfstein and Jeremy Stein published "Herd Behavior and Investment" in the *American Economic Review*, and gave Keynes's intuition a model. Their subject was reputational herding: managers who care about how the labour market judges their ability. In their setup, a manager who mimics the decisions of others protects his reputation, because being wrong alongside the herd is read as bad luck shared by everyone, whereas being wrong alone is read as evidence of low ability. The rational manager therefore discards his own information and copies — "sharing the blame," in the paper's phrase. What looks from outside like a market failing to aggregate information is, on the inside, a crowd of individuals each behaving impeccably rationally given the incentives they face.

A wider literature followed. Andrei Shleifer, Josef Lakonishok and Robert Vishny built empirical measures of how far institutional investors actually trade together. Anat Devenow and Ivo Welch, in a 1996 survey in the *European Economic Review*, drew the map of the field, separating the strands of herding that had until then been muddled together. Sushil Bikhchandani and Sunil Sharma's 2000 IMF survey extended the taxonomy toward financial-market policy. By the turn of the century, the folk observation that professionals move in packs had become a structured account of *why* — and of which kinds of pack-behaviour are dangerous.

## The mechanism

The gears are worth separating, because "herding" names several distinct machines that produce the same clustered pattern.

The first is **informational** herding — the mechanism of information cascades (item 26). Here a manager copies because the actions of others carry information: if everyone is buying, perhaps they know something. Rationally inferring from others' choices, each newcomer stops consulting his own signal and follows, and the crowd's decision can rest on almost no independent evidence. This is herding driven by what people *see*.

The second is **reputational**, and it is the one Scharfstein and Stein isolated. Here the manager may have no doubt about his own information; he copies to protect his standing. The engine is *relative-performance evaluation*: managers are judged not against an absolute yardstick but against each other and against a benchmark. When your bonus, your reputation, and your job depend on how you did *relative to peers*, the dominant risk is not being wrong — it is being wrong differently from everyone else. Tracking the herd caps that risk. You will never dramatically underperform the pack if you *are* the pack.

The third is **compensation-driven**: when pay is structured so that deviating from a benchmark is punished more sharply than tracking it is rewarded, the mathematics of the payoff itself pushes managers toward the index, independent of any belief or any observation of others.

These last two do not require anyone to be misinformed. That is the unsettling part. Informational cascades at least involve people trying to learn from each other. Reputational and compensation-driven herding operate on managers who may privately hold the correct view and rationally suppress it. The mechanism is not ignorance and not contagion. It is *incentive*.

And the mechanism has a systemic tail. When enough managers cluster around the same consensus — the same benchmark index, the same "hot" stocks, the same fashionable risk models — their positions become correlated. The market fills with people holding the same thing for the same defensive reason. That is fine until the consensus reverses. Then everyone needs the exit at once, because everyone is in the same trade, and the crowded trade becomes a stampede. Herding builds fragility quietly, in calm weather, by draining the diversity of positions out of the system one rational decision at a time.

## The anchor example

The cleanest picture is the years before 2008. Across the financial system, institutions had crowded into correlated exposure to American mortgages — not because each had independently concluded the housing market was sound, but because that was where the returns and the consensus were, and standing aside meant underperforming rivals quarter after quarter while the party continued. Citigroup's Charles Prince gave the era its epitaph in July 2007, telling the *Financial Times* that "as long as the music is playing, you've got to get up and dance. We're still dancing." It is Keynes's worldly wisdom stated by a chief executive: he was not claiming the music would play forever; he was saying that a manager who sat down early, alone, while competitors kept dancing and posting returns, would be punished long before vindication arrived.

Underneath the crowded positions sat crowded *models*. Firms leaned on similar value-at-risk frameworks and similar assumptions about how mortgage defaults correlate, often fed by the same credit ratings on the same structured products. When those shared assumptions failed, they failed for nearly everyone at once. The diversity that is supposed to let one institution's error be caught by another's caution had been hollowed out: they were all running versions of the same map, so they all drove off the same cliff. And when the exit came, it came as a stampede — a rush by correlated holders for a door sized for a diverse market. The 2008 crisis was many things, but in this dimension it was institutional herding delivering exactly the systemic fragility the mechanism predicts: not a market of independent experts, but a single enormous crowded trade that unwound together.

A quieter version runs daily in equity analysts who cluster their earnings forecasts. An analyst whose estimate sits far from consensus is conspicuously exposed if wrong, so drifting toward the pack is safer even when private analysis points elsewhere — forecasts bunch, and the "consensus estimate" carries less independent information than its many contributors suggest.

## The flip

This is where the chapter earns its place in the book, because institutional herding is the professional, incentive-driven twin of Asch conformity (item 35) — and it is the machine that turns a market of supposed experts into a mob. Asch showed ordinary people denying the evidence of their eyes to avoid standing alone in a room. Institutional herding shows fund managers and analysts denying the conclusions of their own models to avoid standing alone in a market. Asch's subjects folded to social discomfort; the professional folds to a career calculus. Same surrender, colder arithmetic.

Recall the series' thesis in its cleanest form: the wise crowd and the mob are the same people, separated by a condition. The condition that makes crowds wise is **independence** — the requirement, running from Surowiecki's four conditions (item 20) back to the error-cancellation logic (item 21), that people form and act on their own judgments so that individual errors, being uncorrelated, wash out in the aggregate. Independent errors cancel; correlated errors stack. Institutional herding is the deliberate manufacture of correlation. Managers do not err independently; they copy the benchmark and each other, so their mistakes align and accumulate instead of cancelling, and the "smart money" collapses into one crowded position that crashes as a unit. Where item 26's cascades destroy independence through *information* and item 33's emotional contagion destroys it through *feeling*, herding destroys it through *incentive* — the most durable solvent of the three, because it survives full knowledge and cold blood.

This makes it the precise dark twin of the engineered antidotes. The Delphi method (item 22) exists to strip reputational herding out of expert judgment by making contributions anonymous, so that no one can be punished for dissent and no one can copy for cover. Prediction markets and superforecasting (items 23, 92) reward being right rather than being conventional. Institutional herding is what those instruments are built to defeat: engineered dependence where they engineer independence. It sits behind the efficient-markets story (item 60) as the reason "smart money" does not always correct mispricing — the arbitrageur who would correct it is the very manager whose incentives tell him to join the mispricing rather than fight it alone. It shares its machinery with ensemble monoculture (item 24), where correlated models fail together for the same reason correlated managers do. And it is the human machinery beneath Minsky's fragility (item 62) and the anatomy of bubbles (item 64): the reason exposure gets so uniformly crowded that a small reversal can empty the whole room. The shape of the many holds together here not because minds agree but because incentives forbid them from visibly disagreeing.

## The human weight

Institutional herding carries a hard lesson about power, and it earns a place near the frontier of this series. The comforting story about crowd folly is that it afflicts the ignorant many — panicked depositors, credulous speculators, the mob. Herding refutes that. It shows *elites* herding: trained analysts, chief investment officers, regulators, the credentialled experts who are supposed to be the independent check on collective error. And it shows their herding to be, individually, *rational* — the correct response to the incentives placed in front of them. That reframing matters. If professional conformity were a character flaw, the remedy would be better people. Because it is an incentive structure, the remedy is redesign. Herding is a design failure, not a moral one, which is at once more forgivable and more damning: the system is producing the conformity on purpose, and blaming individuals lets the system off.

The pattern is not confined to finance. Wherever careers are judged relative to peers and dissent is expensive, the same dynamic appears. Bureaucrats sign off on the consensus forecast. Academics cluster around the fundable paradigm. Journalists converge on the accepted framing of a story. Officials endorse the policy that everyone is endorsing, precisely because being the lone objector who turns out wrong ends careers, while being one of many who were wrong together ends none. This is preference falsification (item 34) wearing a suit — a false consensus enforced not among the powerless but among the powerful, each expert privately doubting and publicly conforming because the cost of visible dissent is borne by the dissenter alone. It shades into groupthink (item 43) when the herd hardens into a closed circle that mistakes its own conformity for confirmation. And it feeds the reproduction of stratified order (item 85): an elite that herds is an elite that reliably reproduces the prevailing arrangement, because independent challenge from within has been quietly priced out. The dissent that could correct the collective error exists, distributed across many private judgments; the incentive structure ensures it is never spoken in time.

## The critique

Herding is one of the most treacherous claims in empirical finance to actually establish, and honesty requires saying so plainly. The core difficulty is an identification problem. When many managers trade the same way at the same time, that clustering can mean they copied each other — or it can mean they all rationally reacted to the *same public information* arriving at once, which is not herding at all but the market doing its job. From the outside the two look identical: a wave of correlated buying. Separating imitation from independent-but-simultaneous reaction to shared fundamentals is notoriously hard, and much of the apparent evidence for herding may be well-behaved information processing in disguise.

The standard measures are contested for exactly this reason. The widely used Lakonishok–Shleifer–Vishny statistic, introduced in a 1992 paper in the *Journal of Financial Economics*, gauges whether institutions trade a given stock in the same direction more than chance would predict — but it captures the *outcome* of clustered trading without proving the *mechanism*, and it can register correlated fundamentals as herding while missing subtler forms. Refinements have followed, none uncontested, and estimates of how much herding exists vary widely with the method.

Nor is all herding harmful. Some clustering is efficient information aggregation — the market pooling scattered signals and moving toward a better price, which is the wise-crowd mechanism working, not failing. Not every crowded trade is a bubble; not every correlation ends in a stampede. And the reputational model, elegant as it is, rests on assumptions about how the labour market judges managers that are themselves hard to verify. The responsible position is narrow: reputational and compensation-driven herding are real, theoretically well grounded, and plausibly implicated in the buildup of systemic fragility — but distinguishing destabilising imitation from rational, simultaneous, fundamentals-driven trading remains one of the open problems of the open problems of the field, and confident claims that any particular episode "was herding" should be read with that uncertainty attached.
